---
import Base from "../../layouts/Base.astro";
import PageHero from "../../components/PageHero.astro";
---
<Base
  title="Join the chat"
  description="You're on PalmasMesh — now here's how to talk to your neighbors. How the community channel works, what to say, and the simple courtesies that keep it useful for everyone."
>
  <PageHero
    eyebrow="Getting started · Step 3"
    title="You're in. Here's how to talk to your neighbors."
    lede="Your radio's set up and paired. The fun part starts now — actually using PalmasMesh to stay in touch with the people around you."
  />

  <!-- The community channel -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="wrap-narrow">
      <p class="eyebrow">The main channel</p>
      <h2>One shared conversation for all of Palmas</h2>
      <p>
        PalmasMesh is both the name of our local Meshtastic network and the
        name of the main channel that everyone shares. (What can we say? It
        was built by neighborhood engineers and geeks, not marketing people. 😁)
        Think of the PalmasMesh channel as the chat group for all of Palmas.
        When you send a message there, every neighbor on the channel sees it,
        and you see theirs. It works exactly like a group chat you've used
        before, just carried over the radios instead of the Internet.
      </p>
      <p>
        You can create your own channels if you wish — maybe for your family or
        your yoga group. You'll also be able to send direct messages to specific
        neighbors when you want a one-on-one chat. Both channels and direct
        messages are encrypted, but they aren't equally private — it's worth
        understanding the difference (more on that below).
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- How to join the chat (the link) -->
  <section class="section section-dark">
    <div class="wrap-narrow">
      <p class="eyebrow">Getting the invitation</p>
      <h2>How you actually get added</h2>
      <p class="lede">
        Joining the PalmasMesh channel is a single tap — but you need the invitation
        link or QR code. We don't post it publicly, so that the
        network stays a Palmas community rather than the whole Internet.
      </p>
      <div class="join-card">
        <h4>To get the invitation:</h4>
        <ol>
          <li><a href="/contact/">Contact us</a> or ask a neighbor who is already on the mesh.</li>
          <li>Let us know you're in Palmas del Mar and ready to join.</li>
          <li>We'll send you the PalmasMesh link or QR code. Tap it with your phone, confirm, and you're on the channel.</li>
        </ol>
        <p class="join-note">That link is the same one mentioned in Step 4 of the setup guide — if you've already used it, you're already here.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- What to say -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="wrap">
      <p class="eyebrow">Once you're in</p>
      <h2>What people actually talk about</h2>
      <div class="grid grid-3 uses">
        <div class="card">
          <h4>Checking in</h4>
          <p>"Everyone okay at the marina?" A quick all-clear after a storm, or a heads-up when something's going on — "Tsunami alert just issued for PR!"</p>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <h4>Everyday neighbor stuff</h4>
          <p>Borrowing a ladder, asking which gate's open, a lost dog, a heads-up about the latest HOA policy change.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <h4>Helping each other</h4>
          <p>New folks asking setup questions, neighbors sharing where they bought their radio, range tests around the community.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Privacy note -->
  <section class="section section-tide">
    <div class="wrap-narrow">
      <p class="eyebrow">A note on privacy</p>
      <h2>How private is it, really?</h2>
      <p>
        Short version: PalmasMesh is great for everyday community chat and
        coordinating in an emergency — but it's not a secure messaging app, and
        you shouldn't treat it like one.
      </p>
      <p>
        The <strong>main channel</strong> is encrypted, but the key that unlocks
        it is shared by everyone on the network and isn't really a secret. The
        safest way to think about it: the main channel is like talking in a
        public plaza. Your neighbors can hear you, which is the whole point — but
        so could anyone else who's listening. Keep it to the kind of thing you'd
        happily say out loud in the town square.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Direct messages</strong> to one person are more private — they
        use a key tied to that specific device, so they're not part of the
        shared channel. That's better, but still not perfect, and not a
        substitute for a dedicated secure app. As a simple rule: never send
        anything truly sensitive — passwords, financial details, anything you'd
        be hurt by someone else seeing — over the mesh. For that, use the right
        tool for the job.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Courtesies -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="wrap-narrow">
      <div class="card courtesy">
        <h3>A few simple courtesies</h3>
        <p>The network is a shared resource, and does not have a lot of bandwidth, so a little consideration keeps it pleasant, responsive and useful for everyone.</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Keep it short.</strong> Messages travel best when they're brief — a sentence or two beats a paragraph.</li>
          <li><strong>Be a good neighbor.</strong> The same manners you'd want in any group chat. Real names, real kindness.</li>
          <li><strong>Don't flood it.</strong> Avoid sending lots of messages back-to-back; give others room and let the network breathe.</li>
          <li><strong>Save urgent for urgent.</strong> In an emergency, the channel is for coordinating and checking in — but it doesn't replace 911 when the cell towers are working.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Daily use hint -->
  <section class="section section-dark">
    <div class="wrap-narrow center">
      <span class="pill">⬤ Coming soon</span>
      <h2>Reasons to check in every day</h2>
      <p class="lede" style="margin-inline:auto;max-width:46ch;">
        We're putting together community games and regular activities that run
        right on the mesh — small, fun reasons to open the app and say hi. A
        network everyone already uses is a network that's ready when a storm
        hits. Keep an eye on the channel.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <style>
    .join-card {
      background: var(--tide);
      border: 1px solid var(--line-dk);
      border-radius: var(--radius);
      padding: 1.6rem;
      margin-top: 1.5rem;
    }
    .join-card h4 { color: var(--signal); margin-bottom: 0.8rem; }
    .join-card ol { margin: 0 0 1rem; padding-left: 1.3rem; }
    .join-card li { margin-bottom: 0.6rem; color: var(--mist); }
    .join-card li strong { color: var(--foam); }
    .join-note { font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--mist); margin: 0; font-style: italic; }

    .uses { margin-top: 1.5rem; }
    .uses h4 { color: var(--signal); margin-bottom: 0.4rem; }
    .uses p { margin: 0; font-size: 0.96rem; }

    .courtesy ul { margin: 1rem 0 0; padding-left: 1.2rem; }
    .courtesy li { margin-bottom: 0.6rem; }

    .center { text-align: center; }
    .center .pill { margin-bottom: 1rem; }
  </style>
</Base>
